      <section eId="section_3">
        <heading>What are the policy objectives of the action or intervention and the intended effects?</heading>
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.18in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What are the policy objectives of the action or intervention and the intended effects?</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">The policy objective is to improve the speed and quality of the planning application service provided by local planning authorities by generating a greater income for them through an increase in some of the fees with the greatest shortfall, which will enable them to secure more resources to deliver the service. It is fairer, as a greater proportion of the planning application service is funded, through fees, by those using the service. The intended effect can be measured by the local authority revenue and expenditure returns submitted by local authorities to Government<authorialNote marker="1"><p class="ia-table-text"> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing"><u>Local authority revenue expenditure and financing - GOV.UK</u></a><u> - </u><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</u></p></authorialNote>. Key indicators of success will be an improvement in the speed and quality of decision making<authorialNote marker="2"><p class="ia-table-text"> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-planning-performance-criteria-for-designation"><u>Improving planning performance: criteria for designation - GOV.UK</u></a><u> - </u><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-planning-performance-criteria-for-designation</u></p></authorialNote>. </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_4">
        <content>
          <table uk:widths="7.18in">
            <tr>
              <td>
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What policy options have been considered, including any alternatives to regulation? Please justify preferred option (further details in Evidence Base)</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">If Government did not increase these planning application fees (do nothing option), the planning service would not improve, because the shortfall between the fee and the cost of providing the service would remain. Delays in making decisions on planning applications will mean delays in the delivery of housing and other development needed for economic growth. Planning fees can only be increased through regulations. Our preferred option is to increase householder fees for extending properties from £258 to £528; to double fees for prior approval applications, from £120 / £125 / £258 to £240 / £250 / £516; to increase fees for discharge of conditions from £43 to £86 for householders and £145 to £298 for all other applications; and, to change the fees for applications to vary or remove conditions, reducing those for householders from £293 to £86, and increasing fees for other non-major applications from £293 to £586, and for majors from £293 to £2,000. The new fees will more closely represent the cost to local planning authorities of deciding these applications.  </p>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </content>
      </section>
