      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Problem under consideration and rationale for intervention</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Planning fees make an important contribution to meeting the costs of a local planning authority’s planning application service but do not fully cover service costs. Any shortfall must be financed through additional paid-for discretionary services or through the local authority’s general budget, which in turn falls on the taxpayer. This is a challenge for local authorities currently facing significant budget pressures, resulting in the funding of planning services being reduced in real terms by 36% between 2010-11 and 2019-20<authorialNote marker="3"><p><b> </b><a href="https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/The-local-government-finance-system-in-England-overview-and-challenges.pdf"><b><u>https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/The-local-government-finance-system-in-England-overview-and-challenges.pdf</u></b></a></p></authorialNote>. The Government increased all planning application fees from 6 December 2023, by 35% for major applications and 25% for all other applications. The Government also introduced an annual indexation mechanism, from 1 April 2025, through which all fees will be increased annually by the rate of inflation in the preceding September, up to a maximum of 10%. So all fees will be increasing by 1.7% from 1 April 2025. Despite the 2023 fee increase, income from fees still falls short of the cost of dealing with the applications. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>There is a general imbalance within the current planning application fee structure. Nationally, 80% of planning applications provide only 20% of the fee income. The greatest imbalance is for householder applications, applications for prior approval, applications to discharge a condition and applications to vary or remove a condition. For example, it costs a local authority over twice as much to process a householder application than the fee received, £258 compared to £528.In 2023-24 there were 173,300] decisions on householder applications. Due to the high volume of householder applications, which account for over 50% of all planning applications, the low fee impacts the financial sustainability of local planning authorities, particularly in local authorities which do not receive many larger applications, the fees for which are more likely to cover the cost of deciding the applications.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>There are also some application types for which no fee is currently charged, such as listed buildings consent and works on protected trees, which add to the financial pressure on local planning authorities. In addition to applications for which fees are not currently charged, there are other planning services which local planning authorities carry out without a fee. These include enforcement activity and assessing potential local plan site allocations. Providing these statutory services is a cost burden on local authorities. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>According to the Local Government Revenue Outturn figures for 2023-24, the current planning system cost £1.27billion, of which the planning application service cost £819million. Income from planning application fees was £381million. When also including the fees income from other discretionary services, the overall funding shortfall for the planning application service was £362million (approximately 44%). </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Whilst the income from planning fees can vary for individual local planning authorities from year to year depending on the numbers and types of applications, overall underfunding leads to a consequential under-resourcing of the planning application service, which in turn leads to a reduction in overall performance levels. This holds up development, including housing supply. The income from fees has fallen in recent years, largely due to the decrease in the number of planning applications. The fee increase from 6 December 2023 only took effect in the final few months of the last financial year, so its full impact has not been realised. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The Government recognises that this resourcing deficit needs to be addressed so that local planning authorities have the resources they need to deliver a service that people expect as well as meeting our ambitions for planning reform. Local planning authorities need more resources, so that they can make good, timely decisions. Government also has the objective to reduce the burden on the taxpayer, and for the planning application service to be principally funded by those who use it. Well-resourced local planning authorities will be able to build their capability and capacity, and improve their performance. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Increasing fees to a level closer to the cost to the local planning authority of processing the applications, means the fees are more cost reflective and closer to the true economic cost, which applicants will have to take into account when considering whether or not to take the development forward by submitting an application. The level of the proposed fee increases is considered to be modest, compared to the typical development costs, so we do not expect it to have any impact on the number of applications submitted. Greater resources will support the wider planning service and will benefit all users, including businesses.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The only way to increase fee income is by raising planning application fees. Planning application fees are set nationally, through secondary legislation, therefore Government intervention is required. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>We consulted on our proposals to increase certain planning fees, for 8 weeks, from 30 July 2024, as part of the wider consultation on <i>Proposed reforms to the National Planning Policy Framework and other changes to the planning system</i>. We proposed that fees for householder planning applications should be increased to full cost recovery, estimated to be £528. We also sought views on other types of planning applications for which the fee was considered to be inadequate. We had 1,343 respondents to our question on increasing the householder fee to full cost recovery, from a wide range of respondents, with 72% supporting this proposal. The responses were generally supportive of our proposals. The government response to the consultation can be read here / will be published here - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/proposed-reforms-to-the-national-planning-policy-framework-and-other-changes-to-the-planning-system"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/proposed-reforms-to-the-national-planning-policy-framework-and-other-changes-to-the-planning-system</u></a>. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>In the longer term, we intend to introduce a power for local planning authorities to be able to vary or set their own fees, so that local authorities can recover all their costs for the planning application service. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Rationale and evidence to justify the level of analysis used in the IA (proportionality approach)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The proposals were anticipated to have a business impact and therefore a detailed cost-benefit analysis approach is justified. To ensure analysis is proportionate, only the impacts from measures reasonably expected to have a significant economic impact on householders and businesses were monetised.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Description of options considered</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>We have considered two options for increasing planning fees:</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>1.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Option 1 – Do nothing</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>2.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Option 2 – Increase fees for householder applications, prior approval applications, discharge of conditions and applications to vary or remove a condition</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Option 1 – Do nothing</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Under this option there is no change to planning fees. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Fees for submitting planning applications generally represent a fraction of overall application costs<authorialNote marker="4"><p><b> </b><b>Costs from a 2009 benchmarking exercise by Arup: </b><a href="https://www.thenbs.com/PublicationIndex/documents/details?Pub=DCLG&amp;DocID=290411"><b><u>https://www.thenbs.com/PublicationIndex/documents/details?Pub=DCLG&amp;DocID=290411</u></b></a></p></authorialNote> (including scheme development and application preparation), and an even smaller share of overall development costs. Although fees will increase, due to the annual inflation increase, as other development costs continue to increase, there will always be a deficit between the fee and the cost to the local planning authority of deciding the application because the fundamental, structural issue will not have been addressed.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>In 2023-24 there was a shortfall of £362million between the income for the planning application service and the cost to local authorities of processing these applications. If we do nothing, and despite the annual indexation of fees from 1 April 2025, this shortfall will remain, as both fees and costs increase. This will continue year on year. The continuing shortfall will continue to be met by the general taxpayer, which will put additional and increasing pressures on local authority budgets. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>To do nothing would result in a continued decline in local authority performance in relation to planning, as the income continues to drop in real terms, year on year, with a consequential increasing adverse impact on delivery of new development.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Option 2 – Increase some fees (preferred)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading>This is the preferred option, and the option which we consulted on as part of the consultation: ‘<i>Proposed reforms to the National Planning Policy Framework and other changes to the planning system’</i>, from 30 July to 24 September 2024. The option increases fees for certain types of applications where there is an identified significant shortfall between the fee charged and the cost to the local planning authority of deciding the application. This option will increase fees, with one exception:</heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Fees for householder applications for the enlargement, improvement or other alteration of a single dwelling house, will increase from £258 to £528 (other householder applications, for small-scale operations within the curtilage of the dwellinghouse will remain unchanged at £258)</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Fees for householder fees for the enlargement, improvement or other alteration of two or more dwelling houses, will increase from £509 to £1,043</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Fees for applications for prior approval will be doubled from £120 and £258, where there are associated building operations, to £240 and £516 respectively. Similarly where prior approval is sought for a change of use, the current fee of £125 per dwellinghouse will be doubled to £250 per dwellinghouse (prior approval fees for the construction of new dwellinghouses, which are £418 per dwellinghouse, will remain the same)</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>•</num>
          <content>
            <p>Fees for applications to vary or remove a planning condition will change from the current flat fee of £293 to a three-tier band structure, reducing to £86 for householder applications, and increasing to £586 for other non-major development and £2,000 for major development</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>•</b></num>
          <content>
            <p>Fees for applications for the approval of details reserved by condition, including approval of Biodiversity Gain Plans, increase from £43 for householders and £145 for all other development, to £86 and £298 respectively</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>By increasing these fees the shortfall between the fee and the cost to the local authority of deciding the application will be reduced, easing the pressure on local authority budgets and the general taxpayer. The increase in resources will benefit the wider planning application service allowing all users to benefit. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Policy objective</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The policy objective is to improve the speed and quality of the planning service provided by local planning authorities by generating a greater income for local authorities through an increase in fees which will enable them to secure more resources to deliver the service. This will alleviate delays and barriers to development. With the increased fees covering a larger proportion of the costs of processing planning applications local planning authorities will have a more sustainable income. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The impact of the policy will be seen in the increased revenue generated from planning fees by local authorities. This is submitted in annual returns to government and collated in a table (RO5)<authorialNote marker="5"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</u></a></p></authorialNote>. </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>We monitor the performance of local authorities in terms of speed and quality of decision-making. We would expect to see an improvement in these measures of performance<authorialNote marker="6"><p> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-planning-performance-criteria-for-designation"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/improving-planning-performance-criteria-for-designation</u></a></p></authorialNote>.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary and preferred option with description of implementation plan</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The preferred option (Option 2) will be implemented through secondary legislation. We expect the secondary legislation to be introduced in the first quarter of 2025, and the fee increases to be implemented on 1 April 2025, subject to Parliamentary approval. As affirmative regulations, the regulations will be laid in draft and debated in both Houses of Parliament before they come into force. The regulations do not require applicants to change their processes: the only change for applicants is the cost of the fee.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Monetised and non-monetised costs and benefits of each option (including administrative burden)</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The analysis assumes that the changes in fees will have not change developer behaviour in terms of the number of applications submitted. Under all options, future application numbers are estimated for the following scenarios: </p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>i.</num>
        <content>
          <p>Central scenario: The increase in householder applications observed since the Covid-19 pandemic is assumed to be temporary and householder applications return to the pre-pandemic average and are static. All other application types change by the same proportion year-on-year as forecast private enterprise starts. This approach uses the latest OBR forecasts of private enterprise starts (October 2024). The OBR forecasts only reach 2029/30; application numbers beyond 2029/30 are assumed to be static. We assume the trajectory in net additions lags behind the trajectory in planning applications by two years.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>ii.</num>
        <content>
          <p>High scenario: The Government’s Plan for Change Milestone set out its ambition to deliver 1.5m homes this parliament. It has taken a significant step towards this through the reforms announced on 12th December 2024 to the NPPF. However, further reforms are needed and further detail will follow after the spending review and through the publication of its long-term housing strategy. The Government has set out that given the position it inherited it expects net additions to fall to under 200k per annum in England and then rise quickly from 2026/27. To reflect the greater flow of applications associated with the delivery of 1.5m, we consider a high side scenario using a stylised profile consistent with its delivery. This is not a future forecast or delivery plan. Delivery is assumed to be static after 2029. We assume the trajectory in net additions lags behind the trajectory in planning applications by two years.  This is applied as a growth rate to non-householder applications. The increase in householder applications remains the same as the central scenario.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Average fees data and increases were sourced from the Planning Advisory Service’s (PAS) project data. The data is considered reliable because it provides a representative mix of local authority and application types. The average number of applications was taken for the last 3 years from the PAS data (2022-24).</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>The costs and benefits are modelled by multiplying the expected numbers of applications by type by an estimate of the average fee increase by application type derived from the PAS data.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>To estimate costs from the policy options, we assumed a start date for the policy of Q2 2025, and evaluated the policy up until Q1 2035. All costs were discounted with a discount rate of 3.5% and were adjusted to 2025 prices using the OBR’s estimate of the GDP deflator. This is in line with guidance from the Treasury Green Book. The monetised impacts of each option relative to the counterfactual are presented below. Figures are presented for 2025 PV, and a 2024 price base year.</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p>Option 2: increase fees for householders, approval of details reserved, s73 applications and prior approvals</p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <level>
        <heading><i>Central scenario</i></heading>
        <paragraph>
          <num>-</num>
          <content>
            <p>A <b>transfer</b> from business and householders to local planning authorities via increased fee revenue of c.£56m per year. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
